{"cursor":"1574","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\nA 'patronymic surname' is a surname originated from the name of the father.\n\nDifferent cultures have different way of producing partonymic surnames.\n\nEarly patronymic Welsh surnames were the result of the Anglicizing of\ntraditional Welsh naming system, which may have included references to several\ngenerations: e.g., Llywelyn ap Gruffydd ap Morgan (Llywelyn son of Gruffydd son\nof Morgan), and which gave rise to a quip \"as long as a Welshman's pedigree\".\nThe names Llywelyn ap Gruffydd and such were turned into the kind of Llywelyn\nGruffydds, i.e., the \"ap\" meaning \"son of\" was replaced by the genitive suffix\n\"-s\". Some Welsh surnames, such as John or Howell did not acquire the suffix \"-\ns\", in some other cases the suffix was affixed to the surname not until much\nlater:18th or 19th century. David Hey, pp.92-93 Likewise, in some\ncases the \"ap\" coalesced into the name in some form, as in Broderick (ap\nRhydderch) and Upjohn (ap John). Charles P. G. Scott, \"English words which\nhav gaind or lost and initial consonant by attraction\", Transactions of the\nAmerican Phililogical Society, vol. 25, pp. 82-139 (esp. pp. 91-\n106). P. H. Reaney, Dictionary of English Surnames, 3rd ed.,\nRoutledge, 1991, pp. 462, 3213.\n","linknr":92,"url":"Patronymic_surname","recorded":1374785679,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Patronymic_surname&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Patronymic_surname&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//